---
import GuideLayout from "../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro";
import { GUIDES } from "../../lib/guides.generated";
import { withTrailingSlash } from "../../lib/url";

const title = "CDN Cost Guide: Diagnose the Bill, Choose the Right Calculator, and Validate the Model";
const description =
  "Use this CDN guide to diagnose which CDN line item moved first, route to the right calculator, and keep bandwidth, request fees, and origin egress as separate cost surfaces.";
const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What are the main line items on a CDN bill?",
    a: "Most CDN bills need three separate surfaces: edge bandwidth, request fees, and origin egress or cache-fill exposure if the origin is billed separately.",
  },
  {
    q: "Should I use the guide or a calculator first?",
    a: "Use this guide first when you still need to decide which cost surface moved. Use the calculators once the line item is clear and you want faster scenario math.",
  },
  {
    q: "What changed first when a CDN bill spikes?",
    a: "Usually viewer delivery volume, request-unit growth, or lower cache hit rate. This guide helps you sort that before you trust one blended CDN number.",
  },
  {
    q: "What should I validate before a budget review?",
    a: "Match edge GB, request units, cache hit rate, and origin-side traffic back to billing, analytics, or explicit written assumptions. Then compare baseline and peak windows separately.",
  },
];

const cdnGuides = GUIDES.filter((g) => (g.topics || []).includes("cdn") && g.canonicalPath !== "/guides/cdn-costs")
  .slice()
  .sort((a, b) => a.title.localeCompare(b.title))
  .slice(0, 12);
---
<GuideLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonicalPath="/guides/cdn-costs"
  lastUpdated="2026-04-19"
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <p class="muted">
    This guide is the CDN bill-boundary page: edge bandwidth, request fees, and origin egress should be modeled as
    separate cost surfaces instead of one blurred delivery number.
  </p>
  <p class="muted">
    Use this page when you need to decide what belongs inside the full CDN delivery bill before you compare providers,
    simplify to per-GB math, price requests, estimate traffic volume, or untangle origin egress.
  </p>

  <h2>First-screen triage: which CDN line item moved first?</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>What changed first</strong>: delivered edge GB, request units, or cache hit rate.</li>
    <li><strong>Which CDN line item moved</strong>: bandwidth, request fees, or origin-side leakage.</li>
    <li><strong>Which tool to use next</strong>: bandwidth calculator, request calculator, origin egress calculator, or the full CDN planner.</li>
    <li><strong>What to validate next</strong>: baseline vs peak windows, launch or incident behavior, and the real cache-hit assumption.</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="btn-row">
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/cdn-cost-calculator/">Full CDN planner</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/cdn-bandwidth-cost-calculator/">Bandwidth calculator</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/cdn-request-cost-calculator/">Request calculator</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/cdn-origin-egress-calculator/">Origin egress calculator</a>
  </div>

  <h2>Short answer: what decides CDN cost first?</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>If responses are large or regional delivery is expensive, <strong>bandwidth</strong> usually dominates.</li>
    <li>If responses are small and request volume is high, <strong>request fees</strong> can dominate.</li>
    <li>If cache hit rate is weak or unstable, <strong>origin egress</strong> can erase expected CDN savings.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Guide first or calculator first?</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Use this guide first</strong> when you still need to define the bill boundary.</li>
    <li><strong>Use the full CDN planner</strong> when bandwidth, request, and origin surfaces all need to stay visible in one model.</li>
    <li><strong>Use the narrow calculators</strong> when one line item is already clearly isolated and you need deeper math on that slice.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Keep the CDN guide cluster separated on purpose</h2>
  <p class="muted">
    Provider choice belongs on <a href="/guides/cdn-cost-comparison/">comparison</a>. Blended bandwidth-rate math
    belongs on <a href="/guides/cdn-cost-per-gigabyte/">per-GB pricing</a>. Request-fee math belongs on{" "}
    <a href="/guides/cdn-request-pricing/">request pricing</a>. Traffic evidence belongs on{" "}
    <a href="/guides/estimate-cdn-bandwidth-gb-per-month/">bandwidth measurement</a>. Concept confusion belongs on{" "}
    <a href="/guides/origin-egress-vs-cdn-bandwidth/">origin egress vs CDN bandwidth</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>High-value mistakes that make CDN pages look low-trust</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Mixing <strong>edge bandwidth</strong> and <strong>origin egress</strong> into one delivery number.</li>
    <li>Hiding <strong>request-unit mistakes</strong> inside a bandwidth estimate, especially per 10k vs per 1M confusion.</li>
    <li>Using a healthy <strong>cache hit rate</strong> from a calm week while budgeting for a <strong>launch</strong> or <strong>incident</strong> month.</li>
    <li>Comparing vendors with different traffic profiles, region mix, or cache assumptions.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>CDN bill-boundary workflow</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Edge bandwidth</strong>: delivered GB from the CDN edge to viewers. Tool: <a href="/calculators/cdn-bandwidth-cost-calculator/">bandwidth calculator</a>.</li>
    <li><strong>Request fees</strong>: billable request units. Tool: <a href="/calculators/cdn-request-cost-calculator/">request calculator</a>.</li>
    <li><strong>Origin egress</strong>: bytes and refill overhead still paid by the origin. Tool: <a href="/calculators/cdn-origin-egress-calculator/">origin egress calculator</a>.</li>
    <li><strong>Full delivery model</strong>: when you need bandwidth share, request share, and origin egress share in one place. Tool: <a href="/calculators/cdn-cost-calculator/">full CDN planner</a>.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What to check before you trust one blended CDN number</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Keep one workload profile when comparing providers: same GB, requests, region mix, and hit rate.</li>
    <li>Split <strong>baseline</strong> and <strong>peak</strong> windows so a launch or incident does not disappear into the normal month.</li>
    <li>Validate whether the traffic question is really about bandwidth, requests, or cache-hit decay before changing architecture.</li>
    <li>Reconcile every major input back to billing, analytics, or a written planning assumption.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Monthly planning checklist</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Confirm which CDN line item moved first.</li>
    <li>Separate edge bandwidth, request fees, and origin leakage into their own rows.</li>
    <li>Split baseline and peak windows, especially for launch, incident, or campaign planning.</li>
    <li>Validate cache hit rate and origin-side traffic before using one blended total in a budget review.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Which calculator should you open next?</h2>
  <div class="grid">
    <a class="card2 tool col-6" href="/calculators/cdn-bandwidth-cost-calculator/">
      <div class="tool-title">Viewer delivery cost moved first</div>
      <div class="tool-desc">Use when video, large assets, downloads, or regional delivery mix are the main source of spend.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="card2 tool col-6" href="/calculators/cdn-request-cost-calculator/">
      <div class="tool-title">Request units moved first</div>
      <div class="tool-desc">Use when bots, small objects, or cache-key sprawl make request pricing material.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="card2 tool col-6" href="/calculators/cdn-origin-egress-calculator/">
      <div class="tool-title">Cache-hit decay moved first</div>
      <div class="tool-desc">Use when origin leakage and refill overhead are the real source of the miss.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="card2 tool col-6" href="/calculators/cdn-cost-calculator/">
      <div class="tool-title">Still need the full surface view</div>
      <div class="tool-desc">Use when you need bandwidth, request, and origin exposure visible together before deciding what to optimize.</div>
    </a>
  </div>

  <h2>Failure patterns to catch before procurement</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>One blended rate hides regional price spread and overstates savings.</li>
    <li>Edge delivery and origin leakage are merged into one number.</li>
    <li>Peak or launch behavior is ignored even though it is the first thing finance will ask about.</li>
    <li>Request pricing units are mixed in the same sheet without normalization.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <div class="btn-row">
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/cdn-cost-calculator/">CDN cost calculator</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/cdn-bandwidth-cost-calculator/">CDN bandwidth cost</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/cdn-request-cost-calculator/">CDN request cost</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/cdn-origin-egress-calculator/">CDN origin egress</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/guides/origin-egress-vs-cdn-bandwidth/">Origin vs edge bandwidth</a>
  </div>

  {cdnGuides.length ? (
    <>
      <h2>More CDN guides</h2>
      <div class="grid">
        {cdnGuides.map((g) => (
          <a class="card2 tool col-6" href={withTrailingSlash(g.canonicalPath)}>
            <div class="tool-title">{g.title}</div>
            <div class="tool-desc">{g.description}</div>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </>
  ) : null}

  <p class="muted" style="margin-top:14px">
    Educational use only. Always confirm billable units, real region mix, and cache-hit behavior before turning this
    workflow into a committed budget.
  </p>
</GuideLayout>
